How to Apply These Terms to Your New Programs

If you develop a new program and you want it to be of the greatest benefit to the public, the best way to do so is to make it free software that everyone can redistribute. This means that you can write a new program and then distribute it under the terms and conditions of this license. Besides, you must include the copyright notice in all copies of the Program.

For the protection of your own rights, you must make sure that everyone who receives a copy of the Program understands that they are also receiving these same rights you received.

In other words, you must add this sentence to your new program, so that everybody else has the same freedom:

    "This program is free software; you can redistribute it and/or modify it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by the Free Software Foundation; either version 3 of the License, or (at your option) any later version."

Also, you can add a title and description, but those are merely optional.

Finally, this is not an endorsement of your program, nor does it produce any warranty whatsoever.

The Free Software Foundation has published a list of additional requirements and legalities, which also should be available for reference before use of the license.